Prosper Loan Data Exploration¶

by Mubarak Gwandu¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

  • Prosper is a peer-to-peer lending platform that allows investors to select among personal loans to invest in. They do that by considering a number of factors, which include a calculated Prosper Score that depicts the risk for each loan. The higher the score, the lower the risk, and the lower the interest rates paid by the borrower to the investors.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower income, interest rate, current loan status, borrower employment status, latest payment information and borrower credit history.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main point of interest for me is to evaluate what features are best for predicting the borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (APR) for the loan.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that the total loan amount will have a negative effect on the APR of the loan: the larger the total loan amount, the lower the APR. I also think that the borrowers stated monthly income, loan term, Prosper rating and employment status will also have effects on the APR.

Univariate Exploration¶

I begin with exploring the main variable of interest; Borrower APR.

What is the borrower's APR for people who requested for a loan?¶

The dispersion of APR looks multimodal. There's a peak centered at 0.1, a large peak centered at 0.2. There is also a small peak centered 0.3. Interestingly, there is a very sharp peak between 0.35 and 0.36, only very few loans have APR greater than 0.4.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The distribution of borrowers APR looks multi-modal. Most of the values are at the range of 0.05 and 0.4. There will be no need to perform any transformations as there are no unusual points.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The dispersion of stated monthly income is highly right screwed. Most stated monthly incomes are less than 30,000 but some of them are relatively high, such as the one greater than 100,0000. Interestingly, most of borrowers with greater than 100,0000 monthly income only loan less than $5000. So, the very large stated monthly income may be made up.

Next up, we'll be looking at how borrower APR, Stated Monthly Income and Loan Original Amount correlate with the categorical variables.

In [28]:
# numeric features vs categorical features.

def PairGrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    default_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    sb.boxplot(x, y, color = default_color)

plt.figure(figsize = [10, 10])
g = sb.PairGrid(data = loan_s, y_vars = ['BorrowerAPR', 'StatedMonthlyIncome', 'LoanOriginalAmount'], 
                x_vars = cat_vars, size = 3, aspect = 1.5)
g.map(PairGrid)
plt.xticks(rotation=30);

<matplotlib.figure.Figure at 0x7f503be640b8>

The visual shows that the loan amount is increased with the increase of loan term. The borrower APR decreases with better rating. Also, borrowers with the best Prosper ratings have the lowest APR. It means that the Prosper rating has got a strong effect on borrower APR. Moreover, borrowers with better rating also have larger monthly income and loan amount. Employed, self-employed and full time borrowers have more monthly income and loan amount than part-time, retired and not employed borrowers.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

Loan Original Amount is negatively correlated with the borrower APR, which mean the more the loan amount, the lower the APR. It also shows that at different size of the loan amount, the APR has a large range, but the range of APR decrease with the increase of loan amount. The Prosper rating has a strong effect on the borrower APR, which decreases with the better rating.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

Stated Monthly Income is positively correlated with the Loan Original Amount, it makes sense since borrowers with more monthly income could loan more money. It also shows that borrowers with better rating also have larger monthly income and loan amount. There is an interaction between prosper rating and term. Proportionally, there are more 60 month loans on B and C ratings. There is only 36 months loans for HR rating borrowers.

Multivariate Exploration¶

In my final part of the analysis, I want to start off by exploring how the categorical variables (Prosper rating and term) play into the relationship between borrower APR and loan original amount.

In [68]:

g.add_legend();

<matplotlib.figure.Figure at 0x7f40da9ce5f8>

Term does not have much effect on relationship of APR and loan amount.

In [70]:
# Prosper rating effect on relationship of APR and loan amount
g=sb.FacetGrid(data=loan_s, aspect=1.2, col='ProsperRating (Alpha)', col_wrap=4)
g.map(sb.regplot, 'LoanOriginalAmount', 'BorrowerAPR', x_jitter=0.04, scatter_kws={'alpha':0.1});
g.add_legend();

The borrower APR decreases with better rating. The loan amount increases with better rating. Another awesome observation is that the relationship between borrower APR and loan amount turns from negative to slightly positive when the Prosper ratings are increased from HR to A or better. This may be because people with A or AA ratings tend to borrow more money, increasting APR could prevent them borrow even more and maximize the profit. But people with lower ratings tend to borrow less money, decreasing APR could encourage them to borrow more.

In [29]:
fig = plt.figure(figsize = [9,6])

plt.title('Borrower APR across rating and term')
plt.ylabel('Mean Borrower APR')
ax.set_yticklabels([],minor = True);

For people with B-AA ratings, the APR increase with the increase of borrow term. But the borrower APR decrease with the increase of borrow term for people with HR-C raings.

Going further, look at the rating and term effects on stated monthly income and loan original amount variables.

It seems like there is an interaction effect between term and rating for Stated Monthly Income, the pattern of Term is similar among different ratings. But for Loan Amount, there is an interaction between term and rating. We can observe that with better Prosper rating, the Loan Amount of all three terms increases.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

I broaden my analysis of Loan Amount against Borrower APR by looking at the impact of the Prosper rating. The multivariate exploration showed that the relationship between Loan Amount and Borrower APR turns from negative to slightly positive when the Prosper ratings increased from HR to AA. I then went further to explore the rating and term effects on loan amount, it shows that with better Prosper rating, the loan amount of all three terms increases.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

An interesting observation is that the borrower APR and loan amount are negatively correlated when the Prosper ratings are from HR to B, but the correlation happens to be positive when the ratings are A and AA. Another bugging fact is that the borrower APR decrease with the increase of borrow term for people with HR-C raings. But for people with B-AA ratings, the APR increase with the borrow term.
